author: J.R.
review_text_raw: I've had these for almost 3 years now. They're "decent" if you catch them on sale at $20. ONLY if you have the talent and means to resharpen them occasionally. They are fairly sharp when new but lose the edge quickly. "Razor" sharp? NO WAY! The cheap steel has a limit on how sharp they can be sharpened, and they don't hold the edge very long, before needing resharpened. The scissors are pretty cheap. The handles are hollow, so they have to be dried almost vertically, or you'll get water dripping when you put them in the block. A couple handles have dents, possibly from dishes being set on them in the sink? I have only recently started trying them in the dishwasher, so far, no issues. They're holding up ok, with no sign of rust or spotting. I gave my daughter my much old, much larger set of "decent" Farberwear knives when I ordered these. Wish I'd waited til they arrived, she would've gotten this new set. The block is solid and heavy.

author: Hailey
review_text_raw: I got this set to match my silverware, and when it first arrived, I was really happy with how great everything looked. It was truly quite stunning! However, after about two weeks of using them, I started noticing the color beginning to fade a bit. I keep things simple when cleaning—just soap and water, and a cloth—since I’ve found that using sponges or anything rough can scratch off the color.It’s been over a month now, and I’m happy to say the knives still hold their sharpness surprisingly well since I use them daily. The little holder it comes with fits perfectly in a corner of my RV’s small stove area, which is super convenient.Overall, I’d probably give it four stars instead of five because of the color fading and scratching over time, but if you're looking for a durable, nice-looking knife set, I’d definitely recommend giving it a try!

author: Florence Mason
review_text_raw: These knives are sharp and will stay that way with proper treatment. This is my second set ( bought for my daughter), third if you count the ones stolen off my porch. When you use them do not leave them sitting in water, after the second of third time of use run them through the sharpener, and never use a scratch pad to clean them. My first set and the ones I use daily are several years old and I have many more years to look forward to using them. The are beautiful in my opinion. Use safety with the knives as well as the scissors. The downside to everything you buy is if you don't take care of them with pride you will be disappointed. If you happen to leave them in water and they spot rust, use vinegar and a soft cloth, I have never had to do this with my set.

author: Kayla C
review_text_raw: The Wanbasion Black Stainless Steel Knife Set is a sleek addition to my kitchen. The black finish is modern and eye-catching, and the included covers make storage safe and convenient. The knives are impressively sharp, making slicing and dicing a breeze—I felt like a pro chef the first time I used them!However, I docked one star because the handles, while lightweight, don’t feel as ergonomic as I’d hoped for extended use. Also, while they claim to be dishwasher safe, I prefer handwashing to preserve their sharpness and finish.Overall, it’s a fantastic set for the price and perfect for home cooks looking to upgrade their tools without breaking the bank. Just handle with care—literally!

I prefer the individual knives to a block, as I don't like the extra counter space a block set requires. I ordered the black six piece set and I find them to be very stylish and professional looking.  They are a solid set of kitchen chef knives, especially at the great price, and the set has every knife you'd need for your meal preparation. They'd make a very nice gift, and for under $20, you can't go wrong.

I would not recommend these knives as this is a very dangerous issue that someone will get hurt.  No response from seller.  These are headed to the trash.

review_text_raw: I was given the knife as a gift.  I own many carbon and damascus steel blades, and I was snooty about this being a laser-engraved pattern, not real damascus.  So I gave it to my daughter as a starter knife.  Boy was I wrong.  99% of the time now we don't use my other knives - we automatically reach for this Mosfiata knife.  When the reviewers say "sharp" - they mean scalpel sharp.  Read text through a tomato slice sharp.  The weight and balance is perfect.  The steel takes a super sharp edge which stays sharp for a long time.  IT DOESN'T RUST EVEN WHEN DAUGHTERS LEAVE IT UNWASHED AND WET ON A CUTTING BOARD UNLIKE HIGH CARBON AND DAMASCUS BLADES!!  Oh - did I mention the price?  I could buy 10 of these for 1 of my carbon knives.  Seriously, this off-brand thing will eventually put high-end knives out of business.I wrote this review because a knife this good deserves it, not to mention whoever "Mosfiata" is.

review_text_raw: Edit after only a few weeks of use:It now cuts WORSE than my cheap old knives that I was trying to replace with someone a little nicer. I sharpened this new knife with the provided sharpener and it does nothing for it. I used the sharpener to revive my old cheap ones though and they now work better than this crappy knife does! But I could have just bought a knife sharpener if that's what I actually wanted to happen. I threw away the box this came in so even if I could return it, I can't now. I'm out way too much for one of the worst knives I've ever owned. I'll stick to buying ones that cost way less than this one does and just sharpen them.Original review only after first use:This is definitely better that my cheap knives but definitely not worth paying as much as I did for this. I'm going to keep it and not return it because it's so better than what I have and really need a better knife. But for this price is isn't worth it to buy again or buy from this same brand again.

review_text_raw: I am embarking on my journey as a "real" cook or "advanced" sous chef as opposed to a real chef, and these knives make that journey easier and even more enjoyable.  They are not too large, so they are easy to handle.  They are sharp and well weighted, which makes the tasks of cutting meats and vegetables easier--almost fun.  The price cannot be beat when one considers the impressive quality of these knives--and they look nice.  In fact, they look very expensive, but they are surprisingly affordable.  As I progress to more "advanced" cutlery, I will look for cutlery from this particular brand.  They the best I've ever purchased, and they come highly recommended.

author: Sar Nel
review_text_raw: I struggled with this rating because I like the knife. The knife itself is of good quality - it functions well and as a nakiri should. The handle is well-made and comfortable, the knife is weighted and balanced well to enable good control. This is a sizable blade (as expected for the style) so it needs a “cleaver” spot in the block - keep this in mind.Now, the bad…the first knife arrives with chips in the blade. It’s shrink-wrapped so there wasn’t any pre-use - my suspicion is that the chips happened in transit. So, I returned the first one and awaited the second. The chips were far worse in the second. I would have had to grind off way more metal than should ever be expected on a ready-to-use knife. I kept the first one because I got it on a special deal, and the chips were small enough for me to grind out in a few passes on the whetstone. To that end - I can’t really say if it was sharp out of the box, but it sure was after I worked on it. Definitely returning the one with larger chips, and given that 2/2 of the ones I got were damaged, I’m guessing it’s happening a lot. I feel bad for anyone who gets this and doesn’t have sharpening skills!

author: Evan Coe
review_text_raw: My mom bought this knife for our family but didn’t ask what we thought of it before buying it it was a good sentiment but when I opened it before I even put it in my hand I saw a few problems with it.the first problem I had with it is the fake Damascus etching this is a personal problem I have and it mostly just visual but it also does effect the longevity of the blade. The etching also makes it look cheap which again is just me being picky. When I put it in my hand it immediately felt unpleasant not only is it very heavy but not very well balanced, it feels like I’m holding it too tight just to keep it from falling out of my hands, I felt the edge and it was fairly sharp but not as good as my personal knives which is to be expected from a factory. After first impressions I did a couple tests chopping an onion, tomato and chicken. The knife did about as well as expected on the chicken but under preformed on chopping the onion and tomato, I count the blade was sharp enough to cut the meat and onions if you were chopping straight down but due to the thickness of the blades well as the etching It tended to get caught up in whatever I was cutting. I also found often my knuckles hitting the cutting board before or during chopping I wish the blade was just a bit wider or the handle was positioned higher to avoid this issue. And finally and in my opinion the most detrimental part to the design was the handle. I found it somewhat uncomfortable for a few different reasons the first being the finish it’s gloss which is good for cleaning but not so good for handling it felt as though it was going to turn or slip in my hand when I was cutting especially when cutting the chicken. The other thing that contributes to the death grip I had on it was the fact it’s slightly too circular. That all said for the 41$ price tag it does come with a decent bit of things and if you’re not too keen on hand sharpening knives like myself the sharpener it comes with is fairly decent. The guard it comes with is low quality but a nice add on none the less. The packaging is high quality and although the. Finger guard it’s goofy it’s something,And I wish I could say it was a better knife over all. I’d say it’s worth the price tag if you’re looking for a meh knife with few add ons.I’ll most likely be getting a different knife for my family but if this is what you’re set on it’s  a lot of personal preference

author: C. Wolfe
review_text_raw: Now, I’m no Master Chef…I don’t really know what to look for in a new knife set (the last set may have been a wedding gift). But I knew I wanted two things: something that met our family’s needs and stayed budget-friendly. And I think I’ve found it!After a month, I’m pretty impressed! The block is compact and sturdy, perfect for our tight countertop. And the knives? VERY sharp. I nicked my finger during first use, but I think I was just used to our old dull knives… so be cautious!✅ Compact, space-saving block✅ Solid feel for the price✅ Razor-sharp right out of the box⚠️ Knife handles dulled after a few dishwasher cycles (product details do say hand wash only, but sometimes the sink just isn’t going to get empty otherwise)This set may not be for Master Chefs, but it’s affordable and great for everyday cooking for a small family. I’ll update if anything changes!* Photo 1: Hand-washed scissors next to dishwasher-washed knife on white surface to show dulling on knife handle.* Photo 2: Knife block on kitchen countertop, shown next to a toddler cookbook and two-shelf fruit basket for scale.

author: D Boswekk
review_text_raw: Beware the sharp point near your fingers.  I gave this as a gift to my dad, and he cut himself twice on these.  Higher end knives like the Zwilling Pro are thicker and tapered to help avoid this injury.  I ended up using a hand grinder to dull out this point and it's better now.Also note that the blade is a single thin piece of metal throughout the handle, which has a cheaper feel compared to more expensive brands where the metal becomes thicker near your fingers.Lastly, the tip on one of the knives had a tiny shard that was bent to the side, likely a manufacturing defect.  You couldn't see it with your eye, but if you dried off the knife with a towel it would "hook" the towel and tear out a thread from it.  It would likely cut your finger as well.  Again I used a hand grinder to get rid of that shard, and now it's ok.

review_text_raw: As someone who enjoys cooking at home, I know the value of the tools used to prepare a good meal. HENCKELS is a legendary name in kitchen knives. This 15 piece set has a nice selection of knives to do whatever you need to prepare that next great meal. It comes in a wooden black for easy storage. It’s got knives to cut and trim whatever you’re making for dinner. Chopping, trimming and cutting that steak into bite size pieces is a breeze! HENCKELS has a well deserved reputation for producing some of the finest cutlery ever made. This set is a great value for the money, and I’d highly recommend it to anybody who enjoys cooking at home!

author: RjSelf
review_text_raw: I purchase this cutlery set to replace an older Chicago Cutlery set purchased 14 years ago. Originally I was skeptical of its quality of the knives. Cuisinart has been known for reliable quality electronic kitchen appliances. So when I spotted this set, I had to purchase them. Six serrated steak knives, a bread knife, steak knife, pairing knife, heavy duty kitchen shears and more!! Each have a very comfortable metal handle that is milled specifically to prevent slipping. The display block is solidly made and has rubber feet to keep them displayed in place. Each blade seems balanced and comfortable making them easy to use. I love the serrated everyday steak knives. I have seen similar knife sets from those claiming German Steal and Japanese knives for over 3 times of the cost of these. As an everyday user, I doubt that I could tell the difference between these knives as opposed to those higher priced ones. So far, I am very impressed.

author: Bling Queen
review_text_raw: Overall, I’m quite happy with this knife set. I like that it offers an excellent value for the price and has been a fantastic, affordable addition to my kitchen. The color coding is a wonderful feature that not only looks fun, but also helps prevent cross-contamination while cooking. Each knife is lightweight and easy to handle, making food preparation much more efficient. I particularly appreciate the varying sizes and shapes of the knives, which accommodate a range of cutting tracks, from slicing vegetables to carving meat. The blades are sharp and have held their edge relatively well, though I do find that they require regular honing to maintain their performance. The handles are comfortable, but I wish they had a bit more grip for added safety., especially when cutting tougher ingredients. The only reason I didn’t give it a full five stars is that I would have preferred a more durable material for the blades. They are good for everyday use,. But I’m concerned about longevity with high-volume cooking. These offer an affordable price and is perfect for home cooks. If you do decide to get these, be prepared to hone them and do not expect too much and just keep in mind the price paid for these.

author: OurOpinion
review_text_raw: The set is pleasing to the eye with the darker knife block and bright stainless color.  Thickness of the blade is adequate, easily cutting through meats and vegetables.  Weight is comfortable, not too light nor too heavy.  Sharpness of the blades are adequate and work well.  Set has a nice variety, harder to find a set with a carving knife which this one has.  Storage capacity of course is perfect since the block was made for the set.  There will be no problem with handle cracking or rivet issues since they are one solid piece.  We opted to replace our decades old Henckels with rivets that finally gave way.  Grip is comfortable for long preps.  Wash by hand AND DRY FULLY, otherwise rust will develop.

author: hrh
review_text_raw: I recently upgraded from a basic budget knife set, and the Chicago Cutlery Malden collection has been a huge step up. Right out of the box, the quality is obvious. The stainless steel knives look sleek and modern, and the wooden block adds a warm, professional touch that fits perfectly with my kitchen décor. It looks clean and stylish without being too flashy.The knives are well-balanced and feel solid in the hand. I really like the contoured handles—they’re comfortable to grip and make prep work feel easier and smoother. So far, they’ve cut everything with ease, from slicing vegetables to trimming meats. I also love the built-in sharpener in the block. It’s such a smart, space-saving feature that helps keep the blades sharp without needing to buy a separate tool.That said, I ran into one big issue. I accidentally left one of the knives in the sink overnight, and by morning it had rusted significantly. Not only did the blade rust, but it also left a large rust stain in my sink. That was really disappointing, especially since I assumed stainless steel would be more resistant. I now make sure to dry each knife immediately after washing and never leave them wet or in the sink.Overall, this set has been a great upgrade in terms of both looks and performance. Just be cautious about keeping them dry—these definitely require some care. Still, for the price and functionality, I’d recommend them if you’re looking for a solid, attractive knife set.

author: lovesfireflies
review_text_raw: I stumbled across these knives while on vacation when the AirBnB we were staying at had a set in the kitchen.  I liked them so much that I looked them up and ordered a set for myself as soon as I came home.  That was in March 2019.They felt great in hand and actually made cooking more enjoyable because they performed so well.  We have used them almost daily for the past 7 years and have been BRUTAL on them.  They’ve been dropped; left soaking in liquids for long periods of time; thrown around in the sink; smashed with heavy pans while in the sink; ran through the dishwasher a million times; etc. They have never been sharpened and are only slightly less sharp than when we first purchased them.  They are still very usable.The attached photos show the wear and tear as of today (1/8/26), nearly 7 years after purchase - both front and back. The purple chef’s knife is the most used knife in the kitchen, hands down.  While there has been definite wearing of the coating within the last year or two, the handles still look like the day I bought them.  Everything is tight and there is zero rust (even after sitting in the dishwasher or water for long periods).  Tips are still in tact.  You can’t possibly ask for better performance from a set of $30 knives.  These have outperformed more expensive knives I’ve owned by a mile!I’ve purchased multiple sets as gifts and I’m about to purchase a second set for a new home but my originals 100% still get the job done.  I couldn’t be happier with the quality of these knives.

author: Eric Kocher
review_text_raw: I can only assume this German high-carbon steel began life as the remnants of a pre–World War II submarine prototype, later recovered through some clever global recycling program and reborn by master Chinese builders into this formidable tool.The full-tang handle, balance, and density are impeccable—this cleaver feels less like a kitchen knife and more like a purpose-built instrument. It sits perfectly in the hand, inspires confidence on the cutting board, and looks absolutely striking while doing it. Fit and finish are outstanding, especially at a price point that feels almost unbelievable for what you’re getting.Serious performance, serious aesthetics, and zero gimmicks. Hats off to everyone involved in bringing this knife to life—including the Amazon delivery hero who had it waiting at my door by sundown.Highly recommended.

review_text_raw: This Cuisinart Graphix 8" Chef’s Knife has quickly become my go-to in the kitchen. It feels well-balanced and comfortable in my hand, even during longer prep sessions.The Graphix handle design not only looks stylish but also gives a secure grip when cutting. I appreciate that it’s easy to clean and hasn’t shown any signs of rust or wear after regular use.For the price, this knife offers performance and quality that rivals more expensive chef’s knives. author: Joel
review_text_raw: I am extremely impressed with this 16-Piece Kitchen Knife Set with Block. From the moment I opened the box, the quality and presentation stood out. The natural wenge wood block looks beautiful on the countertop and gives the kitchen a high-end, professional feel. It’s sturdy, well-finished, and holds each knife securely in place.The knives themselves are outstanding. Made from high carbon German steel, they are incredibly sharp right out of the box and slice through everything with ease, vegetables, meat, bread, and even delicate herbs. The balance and weight of each knife feel perfect in hand, making long prep sessions much more comfortable and precise. The ergonomic handles provide a secure, non-slip grip, which adds confidence and safety while cutting.I also really appreciate the variety in this 16-piece set. It covers every need in the kitchen, from chef’s and slicing knives to utility and paring knives, plus the kitchen shears. The built-in sharpener is a fantastic bonus, allowing me to keep the blades in top condition without needing extra tools.Overall, this knife set delivers exceptional performance, durability, and style. It looks elegant, performs like professional-grade cutlery, and offers great value for the price. I highly recommend this set to anyone looking to upgrade their kitchen with a reliable, sharp, and beautiful knife collection.

review_text_raw: This is one of the coolest and fanciest things in my kitchen. It's a beautifully crafted knife that looks more like a sword and it comes with a fitted sheath as well as a wooden storage box.The handle is a smooth wooden curved design made for finger grip and it works for a firm hold.The Damascus pattern on the knife is looks amazing especially when it shines under light.The blade is hard to see, but it effortlessly slices through 2" steak and thick cuts of meat in a single stroke.The long blade makes slicing easy and prevents jagged cuts on the meat so that slices look perfectly straight and even.It is very easy to use and it's easy to clean as well.This makes a fantastic gift for anybody who grills or bbqs steak and other meats.It's more than just a knife, it's a piece of art, with character and utility. My friends and family are very impressed by it.

The wooden gift box is beautiful, making this knife a great present. The only minor drawback is that the knife in the sheath does not fit inside the box as shown in the images, so you need to choose between storing it in the sheath or the box. Despite that, the knife’s performance, craftsmanship, and presentation make it a fantastic tool for any kitchen.

author: AverageConsumerFam
review_text_raw: This review is for the following item: HOSHANHO 8 Inch Chef Knife, 9 Layers 10CR15MOV High Carbon Steel Kitchen Knife, Japanese Professional Gyuto Chefs Knives with Octagonal Rosewood Handle. It cost $75.99 when I ordered it.This 8-inch Japanese chef’s knife has become part of my regular kitchen rotation. It replaced a western style chef knife I had been using for more than 40 years, and that says a lot. I was comfortable with my old knife, but this one is clearly an upgrade.Over time I have learned that Japanese style knives just work better for me. The blade profile sits flatter on the cutting board, so there is less rocking from tip to heel when I am prepping food. That flatter feel makes slicing and chopping feel more controlled and natural.The edge was razor sharp right out of the box and only needed a quick pass on a steel before its first use. I used it heavily for slicing, chopping, and general prep during the first week, and after that my old chef’s knife stayed in the drawer. The edge held up very well and only needed light steeling to stay sharp. After about three weeks of regular use, I touched it up on a 2000 grit ceramic whetstone and it was right back to day one sharpness.I also really like the octagonal Japanese style handle. It may not feel quite as planted as a big western handle when cutting very large or firm items, but for vegetable prep and everyday kitchen work it is noticeably more comfortable. That kind of prep probably makes up most of my time in the kitchen anyway.Visually, this knife looks great too. The blade texture and layered pattern stand out, and the rosewood handle with the brass stud gives it a refined look. It definitely feels and looks different from my western knives in a good way. Overall, this has been a very satisfying switch.

author: Joey chapman
review_text_raw: I received this knife set as a Christmas gift and initially fell in love. The knives look sleek, feel good in hand, and arrived very sharp. Unfortunately, after just over a week of normal household use, the quality issues became impossible to ignore.  Any contact with moisture causes the knives to rust extremely quickly, even with regular washing and drying. Additionally, one of the knives chipped while using the included knife honer, which should not happen with proper steel. These knives are advertised as carbon stainless steel with a stated retail value of $400+, but there is no $400 knife set that should rust or chip under normal use.  The set is often “on sale” for around $200, which now feels much closer to its true value—if not still overpriced. I’ve also reached out to customer support via email and have not received a response after over a week.  While the knives look great out of the box, the durability and materials do not match the premium branding or price point. Very disappointing overall.

I love this because not all fancy knife sets have the serration on the steak knives. I won’t likely have to sharpen these knives very often.This set also comes with a pair of kitchen shears which come in handy for many cooking related tasks. The shears also serve as a nut cracker. I always live and appreciate the multi use kitchen tool!

author: Vine customer
review_text_raw: This set of steak knives set delivers an impressive combination of performance, comfort, and craftsmanship. Right out of the box, the knives look sleek and well made, the polished blades and ergonomic handles give them a premium feel. Once I start using them, the quality really shows. Each knife slices through steak proteins effortlessly, without tearing or sawing. The blades hold their edge well, and the balanced weight makes them comfortable to use during full meals. I also appreciate that they resist staining and corrosion, which makes maintenance easy. Whether you're hosting a dinner party or just want a better everyday dining experience, these knives elevate the table.

author: Leon J
review_text_raw: This set comes with six steak knives, and they look nice on the table. The wooden handles feel smooth and warm in the hand, and the metal blades feel sturdy. I like the curved shape of the knife and the balance; it feels steady when I cut. The knives cut cooked steak and pork chops pretty easily with a gentle sawing motion, and they work fine on chicken too. They are sharp, but not so sharp that I feel scared to use them. I do notice I need to wash and dry them right away so water spots don’t show on the metal. For the price and for home use, they feel like a good value.

author: Jim
review_text_raw: I like cooking steak at home, but my older knives made cutting tough, so I bought this set made for meat. The wooden handles feel balanced in the hand and keep a steady grip when slicing. The weight is even from tip to handle, which helps guide the blade without effort. The high carbon steel blade has a bright surface and holds its edge well. The small serrated section along the edge helps glide through cooked meat without pulling. Each slice comes out clean, and I no longer need to force the knife through the steak. The handle shape keeps my hand relaxed during longer meals. It works well for both soft cuts and firmer pieces.

author: Lilipad
review_text_raw: Comes very very sharp, not quite as sharp as a freshly sharpened knife but out of the factory they did a good job with the stock sharpness. I think the handles on these look fantastic and they all feel very hefty in the hands. The knife block has substantial weight to it, no issues with it sliding around on my countertop. Great assortment of knives for every occasion and the included scissors are nice to have around although there is probably a good chance you have a pair laying around already. I mostly just use mine to make cuts along my pork chops to prevent it from curling.I don't recommend using the included knife sharpener in the block. Those styles of sharpeners tend to always remove so much material and the sharpening you get from them is always subpar in my opinion compared to a good whetstone. Super competitive with the price, good stuff, highly recommend.

author: Arman
review_text_raw: I spend a lot of time preparing meals and have experience with a variety of kitchen knives, so I can provide a thorough assessment of this set. The Quality is excellent, with German high-carbon stainless steel blades that feel durable, well-crafted, and resistant to corrosion. The Knife quality is impressive, with full-tang construction and ergonomic handles that provide stability, comfort, and control for precise cutting. The Sharpness is outstanding straight out of the box, allowing for clean, effortless slicing and chopping across different types of ingredients. The Rust resistance is strong, as the blades retain their polished finish even after repeated washing and everyday kitchen use. The Storage capacity is adequate, with the included block keeping all 15 knives organized and accessible while protecting the blades. Overall, the Value for money is very high for a complete, professional-quality knife set that combines durability, precision, and convenience, making it ideal for both home cooks and culinary enthusiasts.

author: ThomasM
review_text_raw: I’ve been cooking for a long time—mostly grilling and butchering my own meat these days—and I’ve used a lot of knives. I picked up this three-piece Japanese-style set, mostly because I liked the hand-forged look of the high-carbon steel. I’m giving this set five stars because of the sheer cutting performance and feel in my hand. They are a genuinely solid addition to the kitchen arsenal.What I really like is the weight and balance of these tools, especially that large butcher knife. It has a great heft to it, which is exactly what I want when breaking down a pork shoulder or thick cut of beef. The boning knife is agile and holds an edge beautifully. The carbon steel is incredibly sharp right out of the box, and it feels like a real, traditional piece of equipment, not some mass-produced stainless steel that dulls if you look at it wrong. The included honing rod is decent, and so far, a quick run over it keeps the blades razor-sharp.The biggest dislike, and you need to know this upfront, is the maintenance. Because it’s high-carbon steel, it’s not forgiving. If you leave these knives wet for five minutes, they’ll start to show rust spots. I have to make sure they are washed and dried immediately after every single use, or you pay the price. My wife is pretty good about it, but with two kids—my 11 and 13-year-old daughters—it's a constant battle to make sure they don't get tossed in the sink. But really, that's the trade-off for this kind of sharp, tough steel. Given the quality of the blades and how well they perform for breaking down meat and handling heavy-duty kitchen tasks, the value for the money is excellent, even with the required extra care.

author: Mark
review_text_raw: I haven't had any issues with these knives at all. Been using them for a couple of weeks. They arrived extremely sharp, and I do mean extremely sharp. They cut through a single sheet of paper easily without grabbing or tearing it. Probably the sharpest new knives right out of the box that I've ever used. The wooden handles are very comfortable to grip, and provide plenty of control over the knives. I haven't experienced any rusting or discoloration from washing the knives. I think they'll last a long time. I will update this review with me long term experience with these knives after some time has passed. These feel extremely premium to me, compared to your average everyday kitchen knives. Definitely the sharpest knives I own right now, that's for sure. 5 stars. review_text_raw: I absolutely love this set of knives. They are extremely sharp and cut things very easily. Didn’t realize how much nicer it could be compared to my previous set. They are a solid weight and I love the ease of cutting things. The top half of the knives being hammered helps the food not stick to the knife. I will definitely be handwashing these to keep their wooden handles looking beautiful. This would make an awesome gift for somebody who loves to cook. It is a good value for the money and I feel like it is a set that I will enjoy for years. It comes in a beautiful box and is padded very nicely. The knives had a layer of oil on their blades when they came so just wash them before you use them. Highly recommend this set.

review_text_raw: We have a Wickwillow paring knife, and it's great, so no surprise that this Wickwillow chef's knife is also great. The blade is sharp, as with any new knife, but it also holds that edge. It passed the paper test easily, slicing cleanly through a standard 20lb sheet of copy paper. It performed well mincing garlic and dicing onions, then smoothly thin sliced a pork loin roast.I was uncertain about the wood handle, as some other knives have ones with cheap look and feel, but this one has a comfortable grip, good hand feel, and is top quality. It does come in a handsome presentation box if you're looking for a nice gift for someone who cooks. At about $60 (at time of review) this is a reasonably priced high quality chef's knife, great addition to any kitchen.

author: Dale Kim
review_text_raw: This is a very well made chefs knife that is a great addition to our kitchen. It's the perfect size for most tasks in the kitchen. The design of the blade with a cool wood/epoxy handle is very well done and evenly balanced. It feels great in your hand while chopping and slicing. The addition of high carbon in the stainless steel and the 12 degree edge angle makes the blade very durable and sharp as well as rust resistant. It came out of the box razor sharp. One thing to be aware of is that "pakkawood" is not a solid wood species. The handle is made laminating sheets of real wood veneer and then gluing them together with a resin. This actually makes the handle less porous and harder than if it was a solid piece of wood...that's a good thing. Also, be aware that the blade is not a true Damascus steel blade. It is just laser etched with a pattern to look like it. I don't mind as it's still a very quality blade and still looks cool. Because of the design and quality construction, this is a good knife for the price.

author: MS
review_text_raw: I’m super impressed with this 8-inch chef knife! Right out of the box, it looks and feels like something you’d find in a professional kitchen. The blade is incredibly sharp — it slices through veggies, meat, and even tougher ingredients with almost no effort. Definitely a huge upgrade from my old knives.The ergonomic handle is really comfortable to hold, and the knife has a nice balanced weight that makes chopping feel smooth and controlled. I also love that it comes with a sheath and a gift box — it feels premium and would make a great present for anyone who loves to cook.I’ve used it for everything from meal prepping to big dinner recipes, and it’s quickly become the knife I reach for first. For the price, the quality is honestly amazing.Highly recommend for home cooks and pros alike!

author: Double Froster
review_text_raw: This chef knife impressed me right out of the box. The blade is extremely sharp and cuts cleanly through vegetables, meat, and thicker items without any extra effort. The high carbon stainless steel feels strong and reliable, and the edge holds up well after multiple uses.The balance between the blade and handle is very good, which makes it comfortable for longer prepping sessions. The ergonomic handle has a solid grip and feels natural in the hand. I also like the roll forged design since it gives the knife a sturdy, durable feel.The included sheath is a nice touch for storage and safety, and the gift box presentation makes it look high quality. Overall, this knife performs like something much more expensive.I’m very happy with this one and it has quickly become my main kitchen knife.

author: Rodney Z
review_text_raw: Amazing quality knife for a very very reasonable price.It definitely is not a professional chefs knife, but it is more than acceptable for home use.  It's balanced very well, sharp, holds it's sharpness, comes in a durable and reusable storage box.I have a high end knife sharpener and this knife will cut a finger off if you are not careful.Remember, most cuts come from dull knives, not sharp ones, cutting onions is among the top ways people cut themselves, be careful, DON'T PUT knives in the dishwasher.  The high heat and humidity can warp blades and handles, the harsh detergent can cause corrosion, even on stainless steel, knives move and bump against the rack and other dishes during the cycle and the blade can become damaged easily, and reaching in the dishwasher with a sharp knife hiding is a bad idea.  Handwash knives.

author: draagonfly
review_text_raw: This is a truly gorgeous knife. The wood gleams and the steel blade cuts easily through everything from fruit to vegetables to meat. It's a bit on the heavy side, but I personally like that. This would make a fantastic gift as it's presented in a very nicely made box, and I like that it even has a cover you can reuse. The only thing I'm not wild about is how they've etched a pattern into the knife blade. It makes it look like you're trying to fake Damascus steel, but the handle is beautiful enough that it will distract you. One other minor complaint is that there are no rivets through the handle into the tang, but it does at least appear to go all the way to the end of the handle. I'm sure it will last for years to come.

author: ElenaShow
review_text_raw: This serrated bread knife solved a common issue in my kitchen: uneven slices and crushed loaves. The 10-inch blade provides enough length to cut through larger breads in one pass. Homemade loaves with thick crusts are no longer a problem. The knife bites into the crust cleanly and glides through the inside without pulling.The steel feels sturdy and well made. There is a sense of control while slicing, even with firm bread fresh out of the oven. The serrated edge stays aligned and cuts evenly across the entire loaf. That makes portions look uniform, which helps when serving guests.Beyond bread, this knife proved useful for cakes and pastries. When slicing a sponge cake, the blade moves through gently, leaving smooth edges. Frosting stays in place, and crumbs are minimal. This made dessert prep feel calmer and more organized.The handle fits comfortably in hand and feels secure during use. Long prep sessions did not cause discomfort. After slicing, cleanup takes little effort. Crumbs rinse away easily, and the blade looks clean without scrubbing.What stood out most was how dependable the knife felt over time. Each use delivered the same clean cuts, whether working with crusty bread or delicate cake layers. It handled everyday kitchen tasks with consistency and strength. This knife meets the needs of home baking and family meals without complications. Worth to buy.

author: MikeBNj
review_text_raw: INCREDIBLE SET.Let me first start out with, I'm not sure if the block came with a minor scratch or if my wife put it there before I got a chance to inspect in good lighting. I opened it all up in lighting comparable to what you see in my photos and never caught a tiny scratch on the block. The next day with daylight, I noticed it. I don't even care. It's small and maybe I'll color it in with a black paint pen or marker if I care enough. These knives are incredible.So first, like everyone else stated, they're crazy sharp. They're so sharp, my wife doesn't even want to use them. She's a tad clumsy and cut herself on the 12 year old set this replaced. That said, she gave it a shot under my supervision to do some veggie work and she was blown away.The feel and quality of these knives needs to be put in hand to understand. They feel like an artists tool. They got weight to them and a high quality feel. The steel is thicker than my last set and feels stronger. The steel goes from tip to end of handle, FULL TANG. The craftsmanship of the handle and shape of the knives is a beauty. I can't stop putting together dishes just to cut stuff, lol. They feel so good in the hand and just make you want to use them.I finally had a chance to use the "steak" knives on a pork dish I put together and it cut through like butter. They're all insanely sharp, so again be careful handling them. I washed all of them right out of the box and didn't realize I nearly sliced my sponge in half when I was done with them.So yeah, I'll just end that I'm more than satisfied with these. Replacing my 12 year old KitchenAid set never felt better. I did a lot of research prior to buying and it was a close call between going German or Japanese (made in Cali), then thought about Hattori Hanzo and how the Bride got her revenge. Japanese steel baby. These do not disappoint and you will not regret the purchase, I promise.EDIT - I want to touch up on folks with the rust problems and possibly put some fears to rest. These are stainless steel. Even the Cybertruck has owners complaining about rust. The best you can do to prevent it is immediately dry them as soon as you wash them and do not let them sit in water. Think about it, if you fear they're just going to rust out of nowhere, you would have potentially received one out of the box covered in rust. That's not how it works. More than likely the folks complaining about rust have either put them in a dish washer (use at your own risk) or let them sit in a pot of water or something and did not immediately dry them.My best advice using these is immediately wash and dry them off as soon as you use them. It's easy enough to accomplish. I see I'm cutting some pork, I pull out the Santoku knife. I use it. I immediately run it under water/soap, grab my cloth hand towel and carefully dry it off, ensuring no water is left on it and put it back in the block. This can probably solve 99% of the rust problems.

author: J.C.
review_text_raw: This knife arrives amazingly sharp, right out of the box. It has solid weight, a nice thick spine, and a firm handle, making it your go-to knife for just about any cutting, slicing or chopping task in your kitchen. This knife is a workhorse, and when finished, is easy to clean. It'll cut through an entire roast effortlessly, or through a rack of beef ribs. I was skeptical that a knife at this price-point would compare to the "famous cutlery brands" - but this champ is right there with the best of them. Skip the fancy, expensive name-brand knives, and try this instead. You'll save a ton of money, and get a great, everyday knife that should last you for years.

author: Bonwit
review_text_raw: After looking at some of the other reviews, I was somewhat taken aback. Those that included photos were not the set I received, so apparently they sell different versions. To be clear, I’ve included a photo of what I received.The knives have a Damascus steel look to them. Note that this is not actual “pattern welded” Damascus steel, but rather finished (probably laser finished) to give that appearance. This is not uncommon, of little consequence, and the seller does not claim it to be anything other than a Damascus finish. I was very impressed with the packaging of the set, and it would present itself well as a gift. The weight and balance of the set is remarkable, and the sharpness is downright scary. I love the look of the magnetic holder, as it lets you show off the set. The magnet is strong, but the knives release with a simple twist. I’ve owned the set for about six weeks now, and so far, have nothing but good things to say about them. They're still sharp, and zero signs of corrossion. Do be aware that one of the reasons these are so sharp is that, like many fine knives, the bevels are ground to a 17-degree angle, compared to a more typical 20+ degree angle. The steeper the angle, the sharper, but more delicate the edge can be. In the end, it’s a tradeoff, but handle them gently, and I suspect they will serve you well. I intend to report back if this set does not live up to its price point, but so far, I’m impressed.

review_text_raw: El iMarku® 14-Piece Kitchen Knife Set representa un activo estratégico para cualquier cocina moderna, combinando calidad profesional, versatilidad operativa y diseño ergonómico. La inclusión de múltiples tipos de cuchillos y accesorios cubre un espectro completo de tareas —desde filetear y picar hasta rebanar y preparar vegetales— consolidándolo como una solución integral para cocineros domésticos y profesionales.El diseño de mangos antideslizantes proporciona control seguro incluso en condiciones de uso intensivo, reduciendo la fatiga y elevando la confianza en cada movimiento. author: Paul K.
review_text_raw: This knife set is okay for the price, but it didn’t quite live up to what I was expecting. The knives look good and the handles feel comfortable, but the overall quality feels more “budget” than I hoped. They work fine for everyday cutting, but they don’t have the weight or sharpness you’d get from a higher-end set.If you’re looking for a simple starter set, it will get the job done. But if you cook a lot or want something that feels more solid and long-lasting, you may want to spend a little more.
